Title: Bypassing the Quantum Bottleneck: A Theoretical Framework for a Directional Current-Mode Quaternary Charge-Domain CPU
Author: ASWINI BARAL 
Abstract:
As binary CMOS scaling reaches its physical limits under Deep Ultraviolet (DUV) lithography, and quantum computers remain constrained by cryogenic and error-correction bottlenecks, an alternative architectural paradigm is required. This paper introduces "Directional Charge Flow Logic (DCFL)", a novel quaternary (4-state) CPU architecture that computes using the vector direction of electrical current rather than static voltage levels. By leveraging an 8T-2C (Transistor-Capacitor) hybrid cell and introducing a dynamic oscillating 'XYZ' state, this classical DUV-manufacturable processor natively performs analog arithmetic via Kirchhoff’s Current Law (KCL), offering quantum-inspired speedups for optimization, cryptography, and AI workloads at room temperature.
1. The Limitations of Voltage-Mode Binary Logic
Traditional Von Neumann architectures rely on binary voltage levels (0s and 1s). Scaling this down requires Extreme Ultraviolet (EUV) lithography, which is cost-prohibitive. Furthermore, voltage-mode logic wastes power charging and discharging parasitic capacitances.
2. The Directional Charge Flow Logic (DCFL)
Our architecture redefines computation. Instead of voltage, the state is defined by the direction and nature of current flow into a compute capacitor:
State +1: Forward Flow (Current injected into the node)
State -1: Reverse Flow (Current extracted from the node)
State 0: Zero Net Flow (Balanced or idle)
State XYZ: Oscillating Flow (An AC perturbation current acting as a computational superposition/attractor).
3. The Compute Mechanism: Physics over Gates
Unlike standard Boolean logic gates, this CPU uses a shared capacitive node to perform instantaneous algebraic summation. When a +1 current and a -1 current meet at a node pre-seeded in the XYZ state, the DC currents cancel out, leaving the XYZ wave undisturbed. This allows the hardware to natively hold multiple conflicting constraints, naturally settling into minimal energy states like an Ising Machine.
4. Quantum-Inspired Speedups on Classical Silicon
Because calculations happen in a single step (via KCL) without sequential ripple-carries, this chip drastically reduces the critical path for lattice-based post-quantum cryptography and large graph optimizations (like the Traveling Salesman Problem). It achieves this entirely at room temperature, using established DUV manufacturing techniques.
Conclusion & Open Source Call:
This conceptual blueprint proves that classical physics still has unexplored dimensions for computation. I am open-sourcing this theoretical framework to invite collaboration from chip designers, physicists, and EDA developers to build the first simulation of the Quaternary DCFL Processor.
